# Now we can plot our data on top of a nice map from Mike Smith's cool_maps
extent     = [-75, -73, 38, 40]
markersize = 5;

fig,axs  = cplt.create(extent, proj=ccrs.Mercator(), bathymetry=True, isobaths=(-1000, -500, -100, -50, -20, -10), figsize=(10,6), oceancolor='w')
ax_posi = plt.scatter(ru23_rt['longitude'],ru23_rt['latitude'],ru23_rt['depth'],c=ru23_rt['time'], marker="o", edgecolors='none',cmap='cool', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree())

#Add in a title
plt.title('MOO Endurance Line Deployment of RU23');

# Date colorbar code taken from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51160705/plot-time-series-with-colorbar-in-pandas-matplotlib
# Define your mappable for colorbar creation
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='cool', 
                           norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=ru23_rt['time'].min().value,
                                              vmax=ru23_rt['time'].max().value));
sm._A = [];
# Add your colorbar
cbar = plt.colorbar(sm,  ax = axs);
# Change the numeric ticks into ones that match. Time format options detailed here: https://docs.python.org/3/library/datetime.html#strftime-and-strptime-behavior
cbar.ax.set_yticklabels(pd.to_datetime(cbar.get_ticks()).strftime(date_format='%b %d'));

The above plot looks pretty good. Let's look at that code one more time though...¶

ax_posi = plt.scatter(ru23_rt['longitude'],ru23_rt['latitude'],ru23['depth'],c=ru23_rt['time'], marker="o", edgecolors='none',cmap='plasma', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree())

We're plotting in 3 dimensions (longitude, latitude, and depth) but we only see a 2D plot? Can't we just leave out depth?¶

Of course we could, but do we want to?¶

What if instead we visualize our data using all three of the dimensions plotted?¶

Let's take that same block of code from above, and rework it a bit...¶

ru23_de['time'] = pd.to_datetime(ru23_de['time'])

# Create a 'date' column for grouping

daily_means = ru23_de.groupby('date').mean().reset_index()

salt = ru23_de['salinity']
temp = ru23_de['temperature']
time = pd.to_datetime(ru23_de['time'])  # Ensure time is datetime

time_numeric = mdates.date2num(time)  # Convert datetime to matplotlib date format
density_levels = np.arange(np.floor(dens.min()), np.ceil(dens.max()) + 1, 1)
# Calculate boundaries
smin = salt.min() - (0.01 * salt.min())
smax = salt.max() + (0.01 * salt.max())
tmin = temp.min() - (0.1 * temp.max())
tmax = temp.max() + (0.1 * temp.max())

# Calculate how many grid cells we need in the x and y dimensions
xdim = round((smax - smin) / 0.1 + 1, 0)
ydim = round((tmax - tmin) + 1, 0)

# Create an empty grid of zeros
dens = np.zeros((int(ydim), int(xdim)))

# Create temperature and salinity vectors of appropriate dimensions
ti = np.linspace(1, int(ydim) - 1, int(ydim)) + tmin
si = np.linspace(1, int(xdim) - 1, int(xdim)) * 0.1 + smin

# Loop to fill in the grid with densities
for j in range(0, int(ydim)):
    for i in range(0, int(xdim)):
        dens[j, i] = gsw.rho(si[i], ti[j], 0)  # Absolute salinity and conservative temperature

#xlim
x_min = 31
x_max = 36

# Plot
fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax1 = fig1.add_subplot(111)

# Density contours
CS = plt.contour(si, ti, dens, levels=density_levels, linestyles='dashed', colors='k')
plt.clabel(CS, fontsize=12, inline=1, fmt='%1.0f')  # Label every contour

# Scatter with time
sc = ax1.scatter(salt, temp, c=time_numeric, cmap='viridis', s=10, edgecolor='none')

# Add color bar for time
cbar = plt.colorbar(sc)
cbar.set_label('Date')
cbar.ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m-%d'))  # Format color bar as dates
plt.setp(cbar.ax.yaxis.get_majorticklabels(), rotation=45)


# Axis labels and plot title
ax1.set_xlabel('Salinity')
ax1.set_ylabel('Temperature (°C)')
ax1.set_title('TS Plot Colored by Time (ru23_de)')
ax1.set_xlim(x_min, x_max)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Extract variables from ru23_rt
salt = ru23_rt['salinity']
temp = ru23_rt['temperature']
time = pd.to_datetime(ru23_rt['time'])  # Ensure time is in datetime format

# Convert time to numeric for plotting
time_numeric = mdates.date2num(time)  # Convert datetime to matplotlib date format

# Calculate density levels for contour lines
density_levels = np.arange(np.floor(dens.min()), np.ceil(dens.max()) + 1, 1)

# Calculate boundaries
smin = salt.min() - (0.01 * salt.min())
smax = salt.max() + (0.01 * salt.max())
tmin = temp.min() - (0.1 * temp.max())
tmax = temp.max() + (0.1 * temp.max())

# Calculate how many grid cells we need in the x and y dimensions
xdim = round((smax - smin) / 0.1 + 1, 0)
ydim = round((tmax - tmin) + 1, 0)

# Create an empty grid of zeros
dens = np.zeros((int(ydim), int(xdim)))

# Create temperature and salinity vectors of appropriate dimensions
ti = np.linspace(1, int(ydim) - 1, int(ydim)) + tmin
si = np.linspace(1, int(xdim) - 1, int(xdim)) * 0.1 + smin

# Loop to fill in the grid with densities
for j in range(0, int(ydim)):
    for i in range(0, int(xdim)):
        dens[j, i] = gsw.rho(si[i], ti[j], 0)  # Absolute salinity and conservative temperature

# Define x-axis limits
x_min = 31
x_max = 36

# Plot
fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax1 = fig1.add_subplot(111)

# Density contours
CS = plt.contour(si, ti, dens, levels=density_levels, linestyles='dashed', colors='k')
plt.clabel(CS, fontsize=12, inline=1, fmt='%1.0f')  # Label every contour

# Scatter with time
sc = ax1.scatter(salt, temp, c=time_numeric, cmap='viridis', s=10, edgecolor='none')

# Add color bar for time
cbar = plt.colorbar(sc)
cbar.set_label('Date')
cbar.ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m-%d'))  # Format color bar as dates
plt.setp(cbar.ax.yaxis.get_majorticklabels(), rotation=45)

# Axis labels and plot title
ax1.set_xlabel('Salinity')
ax1.set_ylabel('Temperature (°C)')
ax1.set_title('TS Plot Colored by Time (ru23_rt)')
ax1.set_xlim(x_min, x_max)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

#5. What differences do you note with the delayed dataset? Are there any advantages to using this dataset instead of the real-time? What disadvantages are there?¶

The real time hs less data in the center mass of the TS plot. Roughly the shape is the same between the two plots but delayed has much more data. Delayed has more processed and analyzed data which produces a sharper more defined image. Real time data is much faster and can be viewed before the delayed data has been sent off. Delayed is better for more detailed view of data while real time is better for speed.
